John Edward: Language knowledge for world citizens essential
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence. This continued in 2018 with further outstanding examination results and is supported only by individual and joint successes in the areas of sports, art, music and other joint ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), are striving to support their students and their parents at the highest possible level.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education, higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a customized curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and coveted in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely on English only if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current examination results this year show that languages with the highest existing rates are at the top of the rankings of the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who learned foreign languages reached grade A in the higher examinations.
The data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of the students in Mandarin reached grade A during the higher examinations, while 72 percent of the students learning German also reached grade A, 69 percent of the students learning French, and 63 percent of the students learning Spanish.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now regarded as electors as well as STEM subjects (natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers mentioned for the problems of occupation were linked to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly imperative when it comes to preparing young people for their future occupation.
As more and more open spaces require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage through such a lifelong ability in the future.
To be able to communicate directly with people from other countries, multilingual people will automatically take advantage of competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was spoken as the only language of a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for the children of today that we now invest in language lessons.
Children who speak several languages, in particular languages of developing countries, will have better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will teach that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom, for example Mandarin or Japanese, with a view to 2020.
Wherever your child's interests lie, in independent schools there will always be a number of languages with specialised teachers to choose from.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares the children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future looks like.
At this point in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the country’s future, which is why this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as 'international communication'.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il fat bee le faire.
