Germany's new warship delayed again
The latest frigates of the German Navy should have been put into service in 2014 to replace the years of warships from the time of the Cold War. However, according to local media, due to faulty systems and rapid growing costs, it will not be delivered until the earliest of next year.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the leading ship of the brand new frigates of the "Baden-Württemberg" class, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the time called for a military speaker.
The ship should have been put into service as early as 2014, but the ambitious project was plagued by disturbing problems after delivery.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class, already ordered by the Navy in 2007, are to replace the old frigates of the Bremen class.
They should include a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft missiles and sea target missiles, as well as tar technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic reflection.
Another important feature are longer maintenance periods. It should be possible that the latest frigates do not have to return to their home ports for up to two years.
However, the continuing delays can cause the state-of-the-art warships that Germany is supposed to represent as maritime power to be obsolete at the time of their commissioning, says Die Zeit.
The Fregatte F125, persecuted by the accident, got into the headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the yard after its delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media mentioned a number of significant "software and hardware errors" that would have made the new ship useless in a battle situation.
Software problems are particularly serious, since ships of the Baden-Württemberg class are operated by a crew of only 120 sailors, only about half as many as on the older frigates of the Bremen class.
It has also been known that the ship is far too heavy, which results in performance losses and prevents the Navy from carrying out upgrades in the future.
The 7000-tonne Rhineland-Palatinate was apparently twice as heavy as ships with a similar class used by Germany in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project, including the training costs of the crew, has also become a problem.
It seems that costs rose to €3.1 billion, compared to the €2.2 billion originally planned.
The problems with the latest frigates are particularly significant in view of the recent warnings that Germany's maritime power is shrinking.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, military officer of the German Bundestag, confirmed that the Navy is "going out of the capable ships".
Bartels said that the problem grew over time, since old ships were taken out of service but no replacement ships had been provided.
He complained that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could be removed from the Navy.
National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
In a property in the Scottish Highlands, new research is being carried out to show how bats use the landscape in their food search.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future nature conservation activities.
The study conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will search for dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown long ear and water bats in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
In a noise analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and determines which species does what.
A map and a habitat report will then be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are the most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
These data will help to determine the benefits of the habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and to show how to obtain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The bat stocks in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that impact on sleeping places and lead to the loss of habitat.
Windwheels and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-catchers and chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echoing to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the theme of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out inspections, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even set up Scotland's first and only bat reserve in Threeave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's 10 species of bats.
Agent David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
"Here in Threeave we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there is much that we do not yet know about bats, so here and at other goods we are doing these works that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stressed the importance of excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, since it was possible that the involuntary destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and eliminate the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the people to help.
She explains: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and with many of our species we do not know what their populations are like."
