Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province of Central Sulawesi and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a county in the island of Sulawesi, in the north-west of the island of Sulawesi.
In 2017, an estimated 299,200 people lived in the government district, an administrative unit below the province.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of revenue of the Central Sulawesis economy, in particular the Donggala coastal region.
Nickelabbau is also important in the province, but it focuses mainly on Moravali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesis.
Palu and Donggala have been victims of earthquakes and tsunamis over the last 100 years, according to Indonesia's Civil Protection Authority.
In 1938, over 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
West Donggala was hit in 1996 by a tsunami in which nine people died.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific fire ring, and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in the north of Sumatra triggered a tsunami on December 26 that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people in the coastal areas of the Indian Ocean, almost half of them in Aceh.
2005: A number of severe earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias Islands off the coast of Sumatras.
2006: An earthquake with the strength 6.8 shook the south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island and triggered a tsunami that hit the south coast and claimed nearly 700 deaths.
2009: An earthquake with the strength 7.6 hit the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
Over 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with the strength 7.5 shook one of the Mentawai islands off Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozen villages and claimed about 300 people's lives.
2016: A slight earthquake shook the district of Pidie Jaya in Aceh and caused destruction and panic when people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
This time no tsunami was triggered, but over 100 people died from a crashing building.
