Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, says the Foreign Minister
Syria says that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help for the reconstruction of the country devastated by the war that continues for seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the situation in the country was improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
All conditions have now been met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and living conditions.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed help to rebuild the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
