Red Tide update: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are decreasing
The latest Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission report shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more bleak flowering conditions are recorded, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae flower extends over 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinella to the south of Lee County.
Some 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough can be found, but fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
In the last week, middle concentrations were reported in or off the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee District, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier District.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems became known during the last week.
